00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:16.450
Welcome to Snick, Saturday night Nickelodeon.

00:03:16.450 --> 00:03:20.450
Now you'll know what everyone's talking about on Monday morning.

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:27.020
And you can slide in a different nose or mouth or eyes.

00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:31.020
Well, I thought about that when I started wondering who in my family I look like.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:33.020
I mean, do I have my dad's mouth?

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:37.160
Or his nose?

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:43.290
Or his eyes?

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:44.290
No way.

00:03:44.290 --> 00:03:45.290
And what about my mom?

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:46.290
Is that her chin?

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.790
Or her eyebrows?

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:53.330
And what about hairstyles?

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:57.730
I think I'll keep my style.

00:03:57.730 --> 00:03:59.730
As for any resemblance to Ferguson?

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:04.300
Nope. Too horrifying to imagine.

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:06.300
No physical resemblances.

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:08.300
But what about personality?

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:11.300
I have more in common with Sam than anyone I'm related to.

00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:13.300
And he's not like his folks at all.

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:15.300
His dad Arnie likes sports.

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:18.300
And his mom's dangerous Debbie from the roller derby actually likes busting heads.

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.300
Sam won't go near any of that.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:23.300
Darwin may have figured out a lot about heredity.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:26.300
But he never answered that one key question that a kid's gotta ask.

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:28.300
Who are these people living in my house?

00:04:28.300 --> 00:05:22.260
Okay.

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:24.260
I've been sitting here for hours.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:27.260
I'm supposed to make a change in my life and write about it for English.

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:30.260
Which narrows things down to about a billion options.

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:32.260
So why can't I think of one?

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.860
Hi, Sam.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:40.500
Hey, Clarissa.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:42.500
Can I borrow your bike helmet?

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:43.500
Sure, what for?

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:44.500
My dad.

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:47.500
Just in case his head comes in contact with a flying roller skate.

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:48.500
You mean...

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:49.500
My mom.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:52.500
She's only been with us a couple hours and already they're fighting.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:55.500
So much for two weeks of quality time.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.500
Yeah, I guess she'll spend the playoffs staying at the motel across town with the team.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:00.500
Oh, that's a drag.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:03.500
But at least it'll keep her from taking aim at your dad's skull.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:07.500
Only she could be close by and still out of range.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:08.500
Wait a minute.

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:10.500
Maybe she can stay here.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:11.500
I don't know, Clarissa.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:12.500
Why not?

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:16.500
She's been in motels a long time in motel rooms by herself.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:19.500
I think she's kind of forgotten how to live with people.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.500
And I don't want to impose on your folks.

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:23.500
Maybe they won't mind.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:24.500
Really?

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:27.500
Yeah, my dad's between projects, so he's just hanging around.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.500
And our mom's always got along.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:33.500
And hey, I can do my English assignment on her.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:35.500
What English assignment?

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:38.500
You know, the assignment we're supposed to do about changing our lives and writing about it.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:40.500
Oh, right, I forgot.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:44.500
Maybe I'll wear my clothes inside out for a week and see what the reaction is.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:45.500
Cool.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:47.500
Well, now that your mom's coming, I've got my subject.

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:48.500
What?

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:51.500
What it's like living with the roller derby's hottest skater.

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:58.040
Working on that stupid family tree?

00:06:58.040 --> 00:06:59.040
Come on, Pergwad.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.040
Mom said we have to clean up.

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:02.040
That's not quite accurate, sis.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:04.040
Mom said, clean up the mess.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.040
And yet you're still here.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.040
Hmm.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:09.040
How are things coming in here?

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:10.040
Ferguson?

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:11.040
Just about done, Mom.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:13.040
Oh, I have a question.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:18.040
Who is more important, the guy who discovered penicillin or the one who discovered anesthesia?

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:20.040
Ooh, that's a hard one.

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:21.040
Why?

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:22.040
I'll just go with the penicillin.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:23.040
I'll make him an uncle.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:27.040
Ferguson, the guy who discovered penicillin is not in our family tree.

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:28.040
What are you talking about?

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:29.040
I got him right here.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.040
Yeah.

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:34.040
Squeezed between Henry VIII and General Colin Powell.

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:37.040
I feel a special kinship with these people.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:40.040
They're my spiritual ancestors.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:41.040
Give me a break.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:44.380
Ooh, that must be better.

00:07:44.380 --> 00:08:01.360
Watch some ice cream.

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:03.360
Getting a little drippy.

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:05.360
You're going to love it.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:07.360
In shape for the playoffs?

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:09.360
We're going to annihilate them.

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:10.360
And I'll be there for every match.

00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:12.360
Sam, this trip will have lots of time to spend together.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:17.360
And don't forget, I know you want to gab all about what it's like to live with me.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:18.360
Well, I'm happy to.

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:20.360
Look what you're doing for my Sam and me.

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:22.360
Well, you just make yourself at home.

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:24.360
I like the sound of that.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:26.360
Well, where's my room?

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:28.360
All right, right this way to my study.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:30.360
No, no, I'll get that.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:31.360
Come on, Sam.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:35.360
I'll just start to put this in the freezer.

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:40.360
Now that Debbie's rolled into town, I think things around here are really going to pick up speed.

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:44.890
First, honey, is this enough salad?

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:45.890
Should I make more?

00:08:45.890 --> 00:08:50.220
I think it's plenty.

00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:52.220
Oh, it smells so amazing, Janet.

00:08:52.220 --> 00:08:54.220
Oh, it's one of my favorites.

00:08:54.220 --> 00:08:58.660
Bulgur loaf.

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:02.660
Bulgur loaf.

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:03.660
Wow.

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:06.660
You know, why don't I make just a little more salad?

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:08.660
Oh, Debbie, you don't have to do that.

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:10.660
After all, you're a guest in this house.

00:09:10.660 --> 00:09:11.660
Oh, no, you don't.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:12.660
I'm no guest.

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:14.660
I'm Debbie and Debbie dives in.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.660
Well, whatever makes you happy, just be yourself.

00:09:16.660 --> 00:09:17.660
Let's more like it.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:20.660
I don't want to hear that word guest again.

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:21.660
Deal?

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:22.660
Deal.

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:26.670
Oh, did that hurt me?

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:28.670
Oh, not really, I guess.

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.670
Uh-huh, I'm so stupid.

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:31.670
I forgot.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:33.670
That's how we roller derby gal seal a deal with each other.

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:35.670
Oh, certainly brings people together.

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:37.670
Maybe I should make a note of that for my paper.

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:39.670
Yeah, I get kind of carried away,

00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:42.670
but if I do anything out of line, you just let me know.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:50.810
You know, it might be easier if I don't use the tong.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:52.810
Why, you just got to wash your hands anyway.

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:58.330
Anyone bites on anything crunchy?

00:09:58.330 --> 00:09:59.330
Uh, it's not a crude time.

00:09:59.330 --> 00:10:01.330
I think I lost a press on nail.

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:08.740
Okay, Sam's mom has been here four days now,

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:10.740
and I have to admit,

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:12.740
she certainly doesn't fit in typical mom land.

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:16.440
She brought a lovely hostess gift.

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.440
My mom loved the flowers.

00:10:18.440 --> 00:10:20.440
Of course, she loved them more

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:22.440
when they were growing in her planters.

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:26.390
I wonder that pretty well.

00:10:26.390 --> 00:10:28.390
But when Debbie said she was bringing along

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:30.390
a couple of her friends for tea,

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:33.390
mom realized Debbie's got a lot of friends.

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:44.990
And last night, mom had everything ready

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:46.990
for a great Italian dinner.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:49.990
Antipasto, eggplant parmesan, garlic bread.

00:10:49.990 --> 00:10:52.990
For some reason, we all lost our taste for spaghetti.

00:10:52.990 --> 00:10:57.500
Let's face it, this is starting to take a toll

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.500
on old Janet Darling.

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.500
Mom's getting pretty tight.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.500
It's like this, mothers rule the roost,

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:07.800
and Debbie's roosting in mom's hair.

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:10.800
Ferguson, you know, my, uh, my uncle Louis was famous.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:11.800
How famous?

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:13.800
Very famous.

00:11:13.800 --> 00:11:15.800
You should include him in your family tree.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:17.800
Dad, didn't Uncle Louis

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:19.800
install aluminum gutters and drains?

00:11:19.800 --> 00:11:20.800
Yeah.

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:22.800
Why, he wasn't famous for his work,

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.800
but for his lunch.

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:26.800
Sour cream, sauerkraut, sauerbrotten,

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:29.800
topped off with a big ol' slice of Limburger cheese.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:30.800
Gross.

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:31.800
Yeah.

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:33.800
He was such a regular at that deli

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.800
that they named a sandwich after him.

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:37.800
The Limburger Louis Lulu, $3.95.

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:39.800
That's great, Dad,

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:41.800
Brian Gumbel.

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:43.800
What can I say, you gotta do better than that.

00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:47.240
Thanks for dinner, Mrs. Darling.

00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:49.240
Oh, you know, you're always welcome, Samuel.

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:52.240
This is delicious Marshall Best pudding I ever ate.

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:55.240
I just followed the package instructions.

00:11:55.240 --> 00:11:56.240
Really?

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:57.240
Wow.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:11:59.240
You know, watching you in the kitchen

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:01.240
made me wonder, now how come

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:03.240
no one has ever designed a line

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:05.240
of kitchen gadgets for novices?

00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:06.240
You could, Dad.

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:08.240
You know, Debbie cooking in no time.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:10.240
Don't count on it.

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:11.240
Sam's right.

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:13.240
I could teach you, Mom, as long as there's not too many steps

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:15.240
and you don't have to be neat.

00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:17.240
Yeah, the same with Helga Hartwell

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:19.240
taught her mom to skate.

00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:20.240
Who?

00:12:20.240 --> 00:12:23.240
Helga and Leonora Hartwell from the Detroit Destroyers.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:26.240
You mean, I never told you about the time

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.240
I skated against the two of them?

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:31.240
Clarissa, this'll be great for your report.

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:32.240
Okay.

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:35.240
Helga and Leonora were blocking me.

00:12:35.240 --> 00:12:36.240
Wait.

00:12:36.240 --> 00:12:38.240
Oh, oh, oh, oh.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:52.380
When, all of a sudden, I spin around.

00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:54.380
Are you sure you're all right?

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:55.380
Yeah.

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:57.380
Oh, that's a mess.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:00.380
Marshall, I think I hit one of your buildings.

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:06.910
Is it okay?

00:13:06.910 --> 00:13:08.910
A little touch here and there.

00:13:08.910 --> 00:13:09.910
You all right?

00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:10.910
At least let me fix it.

00:13:10.910 --> 00:13:11.910
No, please.

00:13:11.910 --> 00:13:12.910
It's all right.

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:13.910
You sure?

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:15.910
Really.

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:17.910
Don't worry about it, Debbie.

00:13:17.910 --> 00:13:20.910
Oh, maybe I'll walk you home, Sam.

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:22.910
Yeah, we better go.

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:24.910
Don't wait up.

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:25.910
I got my key.

00:13:25.910 --> 00:13:26.910
Night, Sam.

00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:27.910
Good night.

00:13:27.910 --> 00:13:30.480
Good night.

00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:34.480
Well, looks like my gurgling Zagogo is gone, gone, gone.

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:36.480
Marshall, you worked really hard on designing that.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:37.480
No, that's all right.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:38.480
No, it's not all right.

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:40.480
This isn't Madison Square Garden.

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:41.480
This is our home.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:44.480
Don't remember for this, this way.

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:46.480
Yeah, well, it must be all those years on the road.

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:49.480
How do we get ourselves into this?

00:13:49.480 --> 00:13:51.480
I guess I kind of blew it, huh?

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:52.480
Oh, no, honey.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:54.480
There's no way you could have known.

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:57.480
Yeah, it's just two weeks' sport, you know.

00:13:57.480 --> 00:14:01.480
Should be out of our home.

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:07.480
The only question is when she leaves, will we have any home left?

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:09.480
